                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1345" y="750" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1345" y="600" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1345" y="450" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1345" y="300" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1345" y="150" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1845" y="750" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1845" y="600" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1845" y="450" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1845" y="300" width="50" height="50" />
                <rect style = "fill:#ffff00; opacity:0.7; fill-opacity:0.7" x="1845" y="150" width="50" height="50" />
            </svg>
            <p>
            This concludes the first steps.
            We saw how to call opc to create a simple layout in certain formats and technology nodes, and how to modify the creation with parameter files.
            In the next section we will dive a bit deeper to see how we can control more complex layout generation with multiple parametric cells.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>More Complex Layouts</summary>
            <p>
            Now let's start with a simple cell script.
            We will show the script first and then walk through it.
            </p>
            <pre class="opc">local cell = object.create("cell")
geometry.rectanglebltr(
    cell,
    generics.metal(1),
    point.create(0, 0),
    point.create(100, 100)
)
return cell</pre>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>How to get help</summary>
            OpenPCells includes a lot of documentation within the opc tool itself.
            For layout creation, the most important things one would look for are a description of every pcell, the parameters a pcell supports, which cell anchors can be used and what API functions are available for performing common tasks.
            The opc tool can be used to display all these infos:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <code class="shellinline">opc --cell-info &lt;cellname&gt;</code>
                    <p>
                    This shows the cell information of the pcell &lt;cellname&gt;.
                    The cell information is a short basic description of a parametric cell to show how it is meant to be used.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="shellinline">opc --parameters &lt;cellname&gt; [optional filters...]</code>
                    <p>
                    This shows information about a pcell's parameters.
                    A name filter can be applied by adding additional positional parameters to the opc call.
                    This filter is applied consecutively, from left to right.
                    If only one parameter matches, additional informations such as a longer description, the type and the default value are printed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="shellinline">opc --anchors &lt;cellname&gt; [optional anchor names...]</code>
                    <p>
                    This shows information about a pcell's anchors.
                    A name filter can be applied by adding additional positional parameters to the opc call.
                    For every matching anchors (or all, if no filter is given) a short description of the anchor is given, as well as a condition under which the anchor is available.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="shellinline">opc --api-search &lt;search keys&gt;</code> and <code class="shellinline">opc --api-help &lt;search key&gt;</code>
                    <p>
                    This allows searching the application programming interface (API) of opc.
                    The search key can be the name of a function or a module or both, separated by a dot (e.g. <code class="shellinline">geometry.rectanglebltr</code>).
                    The <code class="shellinline">--api-search</code> option searches the list of API functions, potentially printing multiple matches.
                    The <code class="shellinline">--api-help</code> option expects a perfect name match and will only list that one entry.
                    For both cases, when only one entry is listed, detailed usage information will be shown such as parameter list with types, function description, return value etc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="shellinline">opc --html-documentation</code>
                    <p>
                    This launches the HTML-based documentation (that you are reading right now).
                    It contains tutorials, guides for specific topics, pcell information, API documentation and more.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </details>
        @include footer.html
    </body>
</html>
